{{Infobox artist | name = Erna Auerbach | image = Photo of Erna Auerbach.jpg | imagesize = | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = {{Birth year|1897}} | birth_place = Frankfurt am Main, Germany | death_date = {{Death year and age|1975|1897}} | death_place = London, United Kingdom | nationality = German–British | education = Courtauld Institute | field = [[Art History]], [[Painting]] | training = | movement = | works = | patrons = | awards = | spouse = | partner = }}
'''Erna Auerbach''' (Frankfurt am Main 1897–London 1975) was a [[Germany|German]]-born artist and art historian best known for her work on artists of the Tudor-era in England.
== Biography == She was the daughter of the painter Emma Kehrmann (1867-1958).<ref name="DAH">{{cite encyclopedia|editor-last= Sorenson|editor-first=Lee|title=Auerbach, Erna |encyclopedia=[[Dictionary of Art Historians]]|url=http://arthistorians.info/auerbache|accessdate=13 November 2014}}</ref> She studied art history at the universities of Frankfurt, Bonn and Munich, under [[Rudolf Kautzsch]], who supervised her doctotate, and [[Heinrich Wölfflin]]. But she trained as a painter after taking her doctorate. She exhibited in Germany and, after emigrating to England in 1933 (her family was Jewish), in her new home as well. When her studio was destroyed in World War II, she returned to art history.
She studied at the [[Courtauld Institute]] in London after the war, focusing on the [[artists of the Tudor court]], and wrote a second [[dissertation]] on patronage and painting in 16th-century England.<ref name="DAH" /> This would become the subject of her first published book, ''Tudor Artists'' (1954), the first work in modern times to lay out the documentary sources for the arts of painting and [[limning]] in the Tudor and Elizabethan periods.<ref name="Howard">{{cite web|url=http://www.npg.org.uk/research/programmes/making-art-in-tudor-britain/workshops/workshop-1-abstract-6.php|last=Howard|first=Maurice|title=Historiographies for Painting in Tudor Britain|accessdate=13 November 2014}}</ref>
She died in [[London]] in 1975.<ref name="DAH" />
== Publications ==
*''Tudor Artists: A Study of Painters in the Royal Service and of Portraiture on Illuminated Documents from the Accession of Henry VIII to the Death of Elizabeth I'', Athlone, 1954 *''Nicholas Hilliard'', [[Routledge|Routledge & Kegan Paul,]] 1961 *''Paintings and sculpture at Hatfield House'', Constable, 1971, {{ISBN|978-0094576407}}
