{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2012}} {{infobox book | <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Novels or Wikipedia:WikiProject_Books --> | name = The Cats of Copenhagen | title_orig = | translator = | image = The Cats of Copenhagen.jpeg | caption = First edition cover | author = [[James Joyce]] | illustrator = [[Casey Sorrow]] | country = | language = English | series = | genre = Children's fiction | publisher = [[Ithys Press]] | release_date = 2012 | media_type = Print (hardback) | pages = 40 pages | isbn = 978-0-9570684-1-4 | preceded_by = | followed_by =}}
'''''The Cats of Copenhagen''''' is a posthumously-published short story written by Irish author [[James Joyce]] and illustrated by American artist [[Casey Sorrow]]. Written in 1936 for his grandson [[Stephen James Joyce]], it was not published until 2012, when Joyce's work entered the [[public domain]] in certain [[Jurisdiction (area)|jurisdictions]].<ref>[https://joycefoundation.osu.edu/joyce-copyright/fair-use-and-permissions/about-law/currently-unpublished "Copyright Status of Currently Unpublished Material"], International James Joyce Foundation.</ref>
==Plot== The story describes the city of [[Copenhagen]], Denmark, where "things are not as they seem", and is critical of "[[Fat cat (term)|fat cats]]" and other authority figures.
==Publication== Ithys Press published their fine arts edition of ''The Cats of Copenhagen'' in January 2012.<ref name=ithyspress>[http://ithyspress.wordpress.com/2012/02/10/james-joyces-the-cats-of-copenhagen/ "James Joyce children's story The Cats of Copenhagen gets first publication"], ''Ithys Press''</ref> This edition features original pen and ink illustrations by [[Casey Sorrow]],<ref>{{cite journal|title=Art Odyssey|journal=ImagineFX|date=May 2012|issue=82|page=22|url=http://www.imaginefx.com/02287754333292241627/imaginefx-82.html}}</ref><ref>[http://ithyspress.wordpress.com/2012/01/31/casey-sorrow-and-his-cats/ "Casey Sorrow and his Cats"], ''Ithys Press''</ref> letterpress typeset by Michael Caine,<ref>[http://ithyspress.wordpress.com/2012/01/31/michael-caine-book-artist/ "Michael Caine, book artist"], ''Ithys Press''</ref> and handmade paper marbling and binding of Christopher Rowlatt.<ref>[http://ithyspress.wordpress.com/2012/01/31/christopher-rowlatt-taking-the-stylus-for-a-walk/ "Christopher Rowlatt – taking the stylus for a walk"], ''Ithys Press''</ref>
The publication attracted controversy, as the Zürich James Joyce Foundation's Fritz Senn expressed disappointment that the script of ''The Cats of Copenhagen'' had been copied from a letter held at the Foundation without consultation or discussion.<ref>Alison Flood, [https://www.theguardian.com/books/2012/feb/09/james-joyce-childrens-story-cats-copenhagen "James Joyce children's story The Cats of Copenhagen gets first publication"], ''The Guardian'', 9 February 2012</ref><ref>Sophie Douez, [http://www.swissinfo.ch/eng/culture/New_Joyce_book_creates_controversy_in_Zurich.html?cid=32306464 "New Joyce book creates controversy in Zurich"], ''Swiss Broadcasting Corporation'', 17 March 2012</ref><ref>Florence Waters, [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/books/booknews/9074340/James-Joyces-childrens-story-sparks-publishing-row.html "James Joyce's children's story sparks publishing row"], ''The Telegraph'', 10 February 2012</ref><ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-16982445 "James Joyce children's book sparks feud"], ''BBC News'', 10 February 2012</ref><ref>Deidre Wengen, [http://www.phillyburbs.com/blogs/book_checked/publication-of-a-james-joyce-children-s-story-causes-controversy/article_24aa93e0-5714-11e1-8fd0-001a4bcf6878.html "Publication of a James Joyce children's story causes controversy"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120421164558/http://www.phillyburbs.com/blogs/book_checked/publication-of-a-james-joyce-children-s-story-causes-controversy/article_24aa93e0-5714-11e1-8fd0-001a4bcf6878.html |date=21 April 2012 }}, ''PhillyBurbs'', 14 February 2012</ref><ref>Terence Killeen, [http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/frontpage/2012/0208/1224311465140.html "Joyce children's story published in Dublin to dismay in Zürich"], ''Irish Times'', 8 February 2012</ref>
